Reflection: We are working with a dataset that is completely balanced, because all the classes have an equal amount of samples. This should help the training and analysis of our model. When there is a class with a relatively low amount of samples, it is hard for the model to learn this class and it might develop a bias to the class with a high amount of samples. Analysis on a balanced dataset should also give us a better understanding of the performance of our model. Imagine having a dataset with two classes, and 90% of the samples are labeled as class one. If the model would classify everything as class one, we would have an accuracy of 90%. If we would not have a proper understanding of the class distribution, this analysis would give us a very distorted view of the performance of our model.

|### Exercise: RGB feature extraction

Extract RGB values from the image as three lists. 8 values per channel. To do so, you can compute the histogram of each channel with 8 bits, and then concatenate those values. The resulting descriptor will have 24 values (8 values per channel). This feature vector is the descriptor of an images in your dataset.

In [50]:
# your code here
descriptor = np.zeros((nSamples, 24))

for i in range(nSamples):
    # img = np.transpose(dataset.data[i], (1, 2, 0))
    img = dataset.data[i]

    r = img[:, :, 0].flatten()
    g = img[:, :, 1].flatten()
    b = img[:, :, 2].flatten()

    r_hist, _ = np.histogram(r, bins=8)
    g_hist, _ = np.histogram(g, bins=8)
    b_hist, _ = np.histogram(b, bins=8)

    descriptor[i, :] = np.concatenate((r_hist, g_hist, b_hist))

# Inter class correlation
# A measure for variability is the standard deviation.
import seaborn as sns

inter_df = pd.DataFrame()

for i in range(10):
    idx = np.array(dataset.targets) == i
    data = descriptor[idx]
    class_mean = np.mean(data, axis=0)
    inter_df[dataset.classes[i]] = class_mean

sns.heatmap(inter_df.corr())

The Silhouette score is used to assess the performance of using unsupervised machine learning (clustering). We can also use it here to assess the compactness of the extracted descriptors.

You can use the function available in Sklearn;

https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.metrics.silhouette_score.html

Out[55]:
-0.0770694945921322

Reflection: Do these metrics help you assess the degree of similarity among the samples of a category? what about among categories? What can you deduce?

Reflection:

The silhouette score is fairly close to zero, meaning that the clusters are overlapping. This indicates to me that there is a similarity among the different categories. It is however hard to say whether there is any similarity between the samples within a category with only this metric, because the clusters are apparently overlapping, but we do not know how compact these clusters are. For this, we need the intra class correlation

With the intra class correlation, we rely on the single rater ICC's (so ICC1, ICC2, and ICC3), because we are interested in the reliability of a single rater. We can see that ICC1, ICC2, and ICC3 are all very close to zero. From this we can conclude that there is a low level of similarity among the samples within a category. This can make classification fairly unreliable.

The inter class correlation tells us the correlation between the samples from different categories. The ship and airplane both have a relatively strong negative correlation with the other categories. All the other categories have a fairly strong positive correlation with the other categories. The strong correlation between the different categories tells me that they have a high similarity. This confirms the conclusion made from the silhouette score.

I can deduce from these different metrics that the RGB-descriptors might not be a reliable way of representing our data to make an accurate classification model. The samples from different categories have high similarity, which makes it challenging to distinguish between different categories. At the mean time, the samples within a category have a low similarity. This makes it hard to create a reliable classifier.

Exercise: Dimensionality reduction for visualization¶

We can visualize 2- or 3-dimensional spaces. For this reason, you need to reduce dimensionality.

In this exercise you are asked to use PCA for reducing dimensionality.

Link to function to apply PCA: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.decomposition.PCA.html

Create the following two figures:

1) Rely on the first 2 principal components to plot the samples of your dataset.

2) Rely on the first 3 principal components to create a 3D plot.

In [56]:
# your code here
# %matplotlib notebook
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from matplotlib.markers import MarkerStyle

pca2 = PCA(n_components=2)
pca3 = PCA(n_components=3)

transformed2 = pca2.fit_transform(descriptor)
transformed3 = pca3.fit_transform(descriptor)


for label in np.arange(10):
    idx = dataset.targets == label
    plt.scatter(transformed2[idx, 0], transformed2[idx, 1], marker=MarkerStyle('o').scaled(.2))

plt.legend(dataset.classes)
plt.xlabel('Principal Component 1')
plt.ylabel('Principal Component 2')
plt.title("2D Principle Component Analysis")

fig = plt.figure()
ax = fig.add_subplot(projection='3d')
for label in np.arange(10):
    idx = dataset.targets == label
    ax.scatter(transformed3[idx, 0], transformed3[idx, 1], transformed3[idx, 2], marker=MarkerStyle('o').scaled(.5))

ax.legend(dataset.classes)
ax.set_xlabel('Principal Component 1')
ax.set_ylabel('Principal Component 2')
ax.set_zlabel('Principal Component 3')
plt.title("2D Principle Component Analysis")
plt.show()

Exercise: Reflection¶

Reflect on the following questions. Your answers can be implemented in the report for the practical.

- Will you obtain the same visualisation in the feature space for different extracted features?

- Are the classes distinguishable on the feature space when relaying on PCA over RGB?

- What other visualization could you include to better describe your data?

Reflection:

Will you obtain the same visualisation in the feature space for different extracted features? No, when using another method to extract other types of features from the images we will have a completely different dataset that might even have a different number of dimensions. Therefore, the visualization should look quite different.

Are the classes distinguishable on the feature space when relaying on PCA over RGB? The classes do not look distinguishable on the 2D and 3D plot. All the different classes seem to be grouped together in a single blob and I cannot think of a model that could reliably separate the different classes.

What other visualization could you include to better describe your data? Another method to extract descriptors from our images is to detect all the SIFT keypoints. Each keypoint is attributed with the local orientation, the scale, and a descriptor. These descriptors might describe the data more accurately and make the datapoints more seperable.
